  footnotes: []
english:
  title: An Ancient Sentiment
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    To travel early, yet not too early—
    for excessive haste obscures the way.
    Setting out at midnight,
    the road ahead rises and falls in shadow.

    Where do the villages lie?
    Only the distant cry of roosters breaks the darkness.
    When I reach the fork in the path,
    all grows indistinct—
    I cannot tell east from west upon the mountain.

    Only when dawn breaks do I see my folly:
    why did I rush so headlong down this winding road?
  footnotes:
    - This poem plays on the tension between urgency and caution, using the nocturnal journey as an extended metaphor for life's ambitions and the consequences of impatience.
